P2P2Prosper: Analysis of Prosper Peer-to-Peer Loan Data¶

A project built to perform a variety of exploratory and explanatory data analyses about a provided dataset from Prosper, a peer-to-peer loan platform, as an opportunity to practice data visualization in Seaborn and MatPlotLib.

Research project performed by William J Townsend for Udacity's Data Analysis NanoDegree program, Data Visualization course 22 Sep 2021

Introduction¶

This project requires the student to choose a dataset (several are provided, including this one, or one of the student's choosing can be selected) and to perform an analysis of this data with a focus on data visualization of univariate, bivariate, and multivariate plotting. For this dataset, an initial .csv was provided with a wide array of metrics for the Prosper peer-to-peer lending platform. This dataset was generally tidy, but had to be cleaned up in a few areas to facilitate my analysis. With the dataset in hand, students must then explore the data in an ordered fashion through increasingly complex relationships of variables, before presenting an explanatory data analysis with appropriately polished plots.

The nature of this project and what the student is to be examining in each data set is largely unstructured. Students are encouraged to explore their chosen dataset and present their own observations from this exploration to "tell a story" regarding the data. A "call to action" is also encouraged. I took this approach very literally, wandering through much of the data before finally settling on three main elements of the dataset that I wanted to present in my explanatory data analysis:

  • How do prior Prosper loans and friends invested in a loan relate to successful loan completion?
    These are metrics that are unique to the Prosper peer-to-peer loan platform, and better understanding and use of these metrics can provide insight into borrowers and their likelihood of successfully paying off a loan beyond the traditional metrics seen in credits/loan.

  • What value is provided by Prosper's borrower "recommendation" counts?
    This is another metric unique to the Prosper peer-to-peer loan platform, and it is the only visible "reputation" function available to judge a prospective borrower's creditworthiness, similar to such metrics on other sites like a review grade or eBay's feedback scores.

  • What trends can we see amongst the largest investors in the platform?
    Something that came up very organically in the process of this exploration was finding that there are a number of loans being fulfilled in whole by a single investor who is a "friend" of the borrower. This isn't necessarily an indication of anything bad (though it may need to be monitored to make sure this remains the case), as the opportunity to use peer-to-peer lending as an investment opportunity is a feature of some peer-to-peer lending programs. These biggest investors are outliers in the overall dataset, and their investing patterns and results can be informative regarding how the platform is (or can be) used and may be sources of insight that can be applied to the Prosper loan population at large.

Data Cleaning¶

While the data provided here by Prosper is generally in good shape, there are some things I want to clean up here. As an FYI, this spreadsheet contains explanations of all 85 variables in the .csv, which I've trimmed down to about 20 columns to explore in this report. I may not use all of them, but they were things that I thought might be interesting.

  • Change ListingCreationDate to datetime, and sort by this
    Each row in the dataset has a unique 'ListingKey' made up of letters and numbers, which I'll retain but can't use as a meaningful way to sort. To start with, I'll sort by the date the loan is applied for, which will require this to be converted to a datetime object, rather than a string. This is especially useful while doing this cleaning, because variables tend to be generated and populated starting at a given date in time, so it made my visual exploration a bit easier.

  • Fix letter-grades (ProsperRating (Alpha)) for pre-2009 data
    After 2009, borrowers were given a 'ProsperRating' as a letter grade, ranging from lowest to highest, per Prosper: N/A, HR (High Risk), E, D, C, B, A, AA. These same grades existed for borrowers prior to 2009, but were stored in a variable 'CreditGrade' and they weren't used to help generate other variables like the 'ProsperRating' was. I'm going to substitute the provided 'CreditGrade' for missing 'ProsperRatings' where they're available, before making this column into an ordered categorical type.

  • Generate 'credit_score' from upper & lower bounds of credit score
    Borrowers' credit scores are listed only vaguely, with two columns. One column indicates the low bound of the applicant's credit score, and another indicates the high bound, with each bin being a range of 20 (600 - 619, 620 - 639, and so on). Rather than use two columns to represent a credit score, I'll do this with one column. I considered just concatenating the values to publish the ranges, but this could be problematic when plotting because of the length of bin names and the number of bins. I considered just using one value (high or low) to represent the bin, but this could be misleading - if I used low values, a published bin of 620 would contain a value of 638, but not a value of 619. I finally decided instead to publish the midpoint for the bin (610, 630, and so on), as this seemed like the most reasonable compromise.

  • Isolate data to only include loans completed (whether successfully or not)
    When I explored this dataset and ended up choosing to use it, I pretty quickly decided that I wanted to look into measures indicating whether or not someone would be a "safe bet" to pay back a loan. This would require me to look only at loans which have come to some sort of 'end'. The data was organized into several types, and I had to decide how to handle each to gather the specific dataset that I wanted to work with.
    • 'Current': These borrowers have current loans, which they are making payments on according to schedule.
    • 'Completed': These borrowers have successfully paid off their loans.
    • 'Cancelled': These borrowers cancelled their loan application.
    • 'PastDue': These borrowers have current loans which they are late making payments on, but can still maintain their loan and get caught up.
    • 'Defaulted': These borrowers have failed to pay back their loan and are in breach of their loan contract.
    • 'Chargedoff': These borrowers have defaulted and their debts deemed unlikely to receive further payments.
    • 'FinalPaymentInProgress': These borrowers have completed all but the last payment of the loan.
      In the end, I decided to mark those borrowers with only a single payment remaining as 'Completed'. Borrowers whose loans had already 'Defaulted' or 'Chargedoff' were marked as 'Failed' with regard to paying back their loan. Borrowers who were 'PastDue' to varying degrees were considered for inclusion in this category (especially those at longer lengths of time past due), but given that these borrowers could still make payments to get themselves into good standing (and back into the 'Current' group) and had not yet reached the status with regard to a loan contract of being in 'Default', I felt it was unfair to do so. As a result, 'PastDue' borrowers were removed from the dataset, along with 'Cancelled' and 'Current' borrowers. Once done, this variable was made into an unordered categorical type.

  • Generate 'IncomeRange' categories
    'IncomeRange' categorizes borrowers into large buckets, but among these buckets were '\$0' and 'Not employed', which amounted to the same thing. Also, before Feb 2007, this column was either 'Not displayed' or occasionally NaN, before it began being recorded. I checked to see if I could possibly try to generate a general income range for several of these rows, based on their listed debt-to-income ratio and such, but I couldn't find patterns that would let me do so. As a result, I decided to lump both NaN and 'Not displayed' values as 'Unknown', and then cast the column as ordered categorical, starting at 'Unknown'.

  • Generate 'EmploymentStatus' categories
    This variable had buckets like 'Not available' (from pre-Feb 2007, again), 'Other', and occasionally NaN (also pre-Feb 2007). All of these were lumped into a category of 'Unknown'. 'Retired' and 'Not employed' buckets were also combined into a single 'Unemployed' bucket, as I was not interested in the cause for a borrower not being employed, only whether or not they were employed. The column was then cast as an unordered categorical type.

  • Rename columns in a Pythonic fashion
    Arguably, I should've done this before my data wrangling, but I hadn't settled on doing this until I was partway through my wrangling (and getting annoyed by the non-Pythonic column names). At that point, doing this beforehand would've required changing my completed code, so I just did it at the end of the cleaning.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now that the data is cleaned, I can actually start exploring the data. I have 54,435 loans in the dataset, all of which have been either "Completed" successfully or "Failed" to be paid off. I don't have any particular knowledge or experience with peer-to-peer lending, so there is an amount of this exploration that is going to be learning more about the platform for myself with regard to the demographics of who uses it.

Going into this exploration, I left things fairly open in terms of my direction, wanting to be able to focus on relationships or observations that I found, rather than being dedicated solely towards answering specific questions. That said, there were a handful of things that I was paying particular attention to as potentially interesting subjects to dive into deeper.

  • What non-traditional variables are worthwhile indicators of a likelihood to default on a loan?
    Especially with peer-to-peer lending, while there are still elements of this similar to traditional loans (credit scores/ratings, debt-to-income, etc.) there are other elements that we can look at too. For example, I would expect that borrowers would be more likely to pay off a loan if their friends have contributed to the loan, as the person a borrower is defaulting against becomes someone you have a social connection with, rather than a faceless corporation. The ability to check for similar loans through the peer-to-peer system could also be interesting in this regard. Similarly, Prosper's "Recommendations" count could be a telling variable, as people seem to take "reputation counters" of sorts seriously, such as "karma" on Reddit, "Reputation" on StackExchange, "Seller Ratings" on eBay, and many other such metrics, which have been the subject of academic study.

  • If borrowers do default on a loan, what is the likely loss?
    Given the potential risks of peer-to-peer lending, I'm curious if people default earlier or later on in their loans. Defaulting on a loan early on could indicate that the borrower was never particularly committed to trying to pay the loan, while defaulting later could indicate that they are legitimately trying. I'd love to have a "normal" for traditional bank loans to compare any such number to.

  • How do non-traditional and traditional metrics interact?
    This is more of a curiosity than anything I expect to find a significant observation about. As mentioned, I'm not particularly knowledgeable about peer-to-peer lending (and I wouldn't say that I'm any more knowledgeable than "average" on traditional lending, for that matter), so I'm curious to see what exists between these metrics.

In [19]:
# Bar plot for ProsperRating
sns.countplot(data = prosper, x= 'prosper_rating', color = 'coral');

This is the distribution of 'Prosper Ratings' throughout the dataset, as their holistic "credit grade". It's definitely a bit right skewed, which I would've assumed to be the case (people with poor credit would be more likely to seek non-traditional loans), but not as much as I would've thought. I am surprised at both the lower number of people using Prosper at very low Prosper Ratings (HR & E), and at the number of people using it at high ratings (A & AA).

3/5 year loans can be used for a number of things - buying a car, starting a business, home renovations, paying off higher interest debts, etc. One possible explanation is that people who have very bad credit are simply not in a position to be getting these loans and are instead trying to make it check-to-check, or at least may not be aware that this is an option for them and instead end up dealing with shady car dealers, payday lenders, etc. That is entirely speculation on my part, but it makes intuitive sense to me. What is maybe more curious is why people with good credit are using Prosper, instead of going to their bank. The thought occurred to me that this may be an issue of banks making it cumbersome or irritating to get a loan, but that is how banks make money and as Lupe Fiasco once said, "Crooked banks around the world will gladly give a loan today, so if you ever miss a payment they can take your home away". The other possibility that occurred to me is that Prosper may simply be cheaper for those borrowers with good credit. I can see where this would be more likely with banks, which are for-profit institutions with bloated corporate structures and shareholder dividends to pay, which Prosper would not have to deal with. I'm less confident that this might be the case with credit unions or other not-for-profit bank/loan institutions. However, if Prosper is dealing with a number of people who are relatively bad credit risks, perhaps it is worth it to cut a deal to the people who constitute "safe bets"? This is actually a very interesting question that I'd love to know more about.

In [20]:
# Histogram for credit_score
# Set bins for every 20 from 300 - 900 (possible credit scores, each score in 1 bin)
c_bins = np.arange(300, 900 + 20, 20)
plt.hist(data = prosper, x = 'credit_score', color = 'coral', bins = c_bins);

Where "Prosper Rating" is a proprietary "credit score" that can incorporate other factors provided to their platform, we see a (mostly) similar distribution here with the actual FICO credit scores of borrowers, with some minor changes. The FICO credit score ranges from 300 - 850, and there are a number of different scales out there with slightly different "breakpoints" for what constitutes different "bins" with regard to labelling one's credit as "good", "bad", "etc". These scales are relatively consistent, however, in having "Fair" credit starting in the mid 600's, and "Bad" credit being a small range just below that (usually the mid/high 500's), and then "Very Bad" being anything below.

Looking at the actual values for each bin in this histogram, the overall peak occurs at a credit score of 650 (6263 loans). This would likely be what Prosper was defining as "Fair" or "Average" credit. The drop off to the left (values of 610 and 630) would most likely be the very narrow band of "Bad" credit, and everything else to the left (another significant drop off) would be "Very Bad". This drop off doesn't seem particularly unusual to me, given how credit (at least in the US) works and how mismanaging your credit or making big mistakes with your credit is the kind of predicament that quickly compounds and becomes a larger problem. A local peak is apparent at credit score of 530 (1592 loans), which might be related to the very same idea that if you mess up your credit score, you're likely going to do so in severe fashion. While the count of borrowers drops off significantly as we look at bad credit scores, we see it slope off much more gently with higher credit scores, similar to what was seen above with the Prosper Ratings.

Of the four peaks seen on the histogram, the interior two appear to be making up the outside edges of the interquartile range seen in the box plot. I would suspect that these peaks in APR represent "binning" of borrowers by the criteria Prosper deems most important, with small adjustments made from by factors deemed less significant.

This, much like the data on credit scores and Prosper Ratings, was interesting and somewhat surprising. Peer-to-peer lending is often seen as a mecahnism for people who cannot normally get loans through traditional means, usually on account of poor credit or non-traditional employment circumstances. The idea that fewer borrowers on Prosper were making under \$25,000 (10.5\% of this dataset) than were making over \\$100,000 (11.2%) really undercuts that perception.

While one can certainly have a high paying job and poor credit, or vice versa, I would expect people with high paying jobs (non-traditional or not) to be able to get traditional loans. Financial liquidity from a large paycheck certainly makes it easier to avoid tanking one's credit, and banks look more favorably on extending credit to someone who they know makes enough money to pay them back. That people who presumably have the ability to get traditional loans are opting for a non-traditional route dredges up the same questions from the sections on credit scores and Prosper Ratings - why?

# Copy prosper dataframe to new dataframe of failed loans

fail_df['princip_pct_lost'] = fail_df['lost_principal'] / fail_df['loan_amt']
# Calculate percentage of principal loan amount paid
fail_df['princip_pct_paid'] = (1 - fail_df['princip_pct_lost'])

I was curious about what proportion of a loan amount is being lost on each failing loan. This could be important to investors because on two loans of \$10,000, a borrower who pays off \\$8,000 of the principal is far preferable to a borrower who only pays off \$2,000 of the principal. In essence, while both are marked as "failed" loans, one has failed more grievously than the other, and the investors have suffered a larger loss as a result. Across the entire dataset, we can see that on average amongst failed loans, about 29\% of the principal is paid by the borrower, leaving a loss of 71\% on the principal of the loan.

Prosper also offers an ability for friends to contribute to a borrower's loan request, which is quantified both in terms of how many friends are putting in money and how much has been contributed in total from the borrower's friends. This could indicate an increased level of trust for the borrower, with a sentiment like "my friends believe in me, so should you!". This could also indicate a level of investment for the borrower that may make them more likely to pay back a loan, because now they have social capital at risk in the form of friends willing to loan them money, on top of the normal risks of a loan.

One thing that was particularly interesting was the values donated by some people's friends. The vast majority of "friend investments" are about what you might expect - a hundred here, a few hundred there, a couple listings which manage to get a couple thousand out of friends and family, that sort of thing. In looking at the values for this variable, the largest amount invested by a friend was \$25,000. This piqued my curiosity and I looked at the loan, shown above. This was actually a listing made by someone with an income of over \\$100,000 per year and a middle credit score, asking for \$25,000 and having it all financed by one friend. I found this odd and started digging through some of the other high-friend-investment loans and found 95 other similar loans, financed in whole by a single friend-investment. We'll cover this in more detail near the end of this report.

I was really surprised by this, but I could see some reasons why people may do this. The very first reason that occurred to me, which may say more about me than the data itself, is money laundering. This doesn't appear to be happening in large enough amounts for that to be the case, and its probably not the most efficient way to do so in a world with increasing acceptance of cryptocurrency. (Arguably, maybe that makes it a better way to do so - who's watching Prosper, when you could go after the bigshots on Bitcoin?) The more likely option here is that this could be a way to "formalize" a loan between friends without lawyers and personal contracts, doing so through an intermediary service that handles the payback while still allowing you to help a friend out.

What's interesting about that is that of these 95 loans funded entirely by friends, 20 of them were "Failed". That failure rate of about 21\% is better than the data for the entire dataset (about 30\% of loans marked as "Failed"), but not that much better, especially with the small sample size at play here. Having retained the net principal lost in this dataset, I calculated the average percentage of principal lost across those 20 "Failed" loans, and found that the average principal lost in these friend-exclusive loans was just shy of 52\% of the loan amount.

Bivariate Exploration¶

Having looked at each of the variables in this data by themselves, it's time to start looking at how these variables interact with each other.

In [36]:
# Plotting prosper_rating and credit score
plt.figure(figsize = [12, 4])

# Plot 1: box plot of prosper_rating vs credit_score
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sns.boxplot(data = prosper, x = 'prosper_rating', y = 'credit_score', color = 'coral');

# Plot 2: violin plot of prosper_rating vs credit_score
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
sns.violinplot(data = prosper, x = 'prosper_rating', y = 'credit_score', color = 'coral', inner = 'quartile');

I had expected that Prosper rating and credit scores would mirror each other fairly closely, and this seems to be the case based on these graphs, based on how the center of each Prosper rating population increases in credit score as the Prosper rating goes up. The idea behind the Prosper rating is that it can incorporate more factors than are necessarily included in one's credit score alone, which I would expect to lead to an effect where the credit score would serve as a strong anchor for Prosper rating, and other metrics would pull that rating up or down to generate a more accurate picture of ones creditworthiness. This assumption of the strength of the credit score as a strong anchor is, admittedly, based on the way that one's credit rating is portrayed as the be-all, end-all of the credit/loan industry, which is certainly an oversimplification.

In the above violin plot, its very evident how there are central credit scores in each Prosper rating (this effect is somewhat overstated by the binning of credit scores in increments of 20: 710, 730, 750...) where we see the "meat" of each category occurring, but then smaller peaks outside of that. Those smaller peaks indicate the less-common bins of credit scores for each category, being pushed and pulled by the other factors that Prosper rating uses to generate a final letter grade. For example, a borrower with a credit score of 700 would likely land in the 'B' Prosper Rating (center of that distribution), but secondary factors in their favor pushe them to the right, where they would be at the bottom of the "A" distribution. Conversely, secondary factors not in their favor push them left, into the top of the "C" distribution.

It is interesting how the populations for "E" and "HR" are spread out into such wide ranging distributions, having two distinct and very distant (relatively speaking) peaks. I'm unsure what one could do that would make Prosper deem them to having such a low Prosper rating, which would not also negatively impact their credit, but we see peaks occurring in the range of 700 credit scores. With the "HR" bin in particular, if this is being used as more of a "Unknown" bin than a "These are truly high risk" bin for identifying borrowers, this could explain the wide range, though this seems like an odd practice to me. Examining why this relationship breaks down at the low end of the scale would require data and knowledge that are not available to me.

Plotting these traditional variables against credit rating was intended to see how strongly these metrics related to the credit score. Open lines of credit was plotted on a log scale, based on the observations for how it normalized under such circumstances in the univariate exploration. All four seem to be somewhat weak, but do have observable relationships.

Borrower apr increases as borrower credit score decreases, though this cuts off abruptly around 0.32 APR and credit scores of < 500. While you might expect this relationship to continue downward, this would likely indicate a refusal to work with people of sufficiently awful credit. To get APRs larger than 0.32, it seems that borrowers have to be maintaining a credit score that indicates at least an effort to maintain or improve their credit. As credit score is one of the primary factors influencing one's final APR on a loan, this makes sense.

Open lines of credit actually indicates an unintuitive truths about building one's credit score. Having very few lines of credit excludes one from getting the highest scores, but once you reach a certain number of credit lines, the highest credit scores become possible to reach. After that point, increasing lines of credit seem to be somewhat normally distributed across the range of credit scores.

The debt-to-income ratio appears to be somewhat normally distributed at the range where the vast majority of the data sits (2:1, or less). The distribution at a ratio of 10:1 is actually relatively centered on the scale of credit scores, which was a surprise. While I'm not sure why this is, I'm also not sure how one continues getting credit extended to them to end up with such a debt-to-income ratio.

Income appeared to have the strongest relationship with credit score, though not as strong as I'd expected. This makes sense, as it is easier to pay one's debts with increased financial flexibility from having a higher income.

Having looked at the traditional variables that contribute to credit score and Prosper rating, now I want to take a look at how each of these relate to successful (or unsuccessful) completion of a loan, which is what they're ultimately intended as measures for.

Here, we can clearly see how both credit score and Prosper rating are both clearly associated with loan completion. As each credit-worthiness score increases, the probability of successful loan completion steadily increases, and vice versa for loan failure.

It's hard to say if either of these two metrics is "better" than the other at predicting successful loan completion. The more granular nature of credit score versus Prosper rating intuitively seems like it would be the more accurate assessment of credit-worthiness, but this might depend upon the specific use case. Humans can struggle with perceiving the magnitude of small differences (say, from a credit score of 670 to 690), especially on non-standard scales, but the less-granular "binning" of the Prosper rating could make this an easier thing to perceptually distinguish.

Dead End Detour: Credit Binning¶

Given the issues with the differences in granularity between credit score and Prosper rating letter grades, I did try to address this by "binning" the credit scores to create a 7-bin categorization of credit scores, similar to the distribution of Prosper grades. To do this, I took the value counts for each credit score, and I added up their loan status failures until they were relatively near to the number of failures in the corresponding Prosper rating bin. I used failures because I was able to more closely approximate the values across both metrics than I was with successes. This turned out to create a distribution like so:

B 1973 1183 730
C 2858 3327 690, 710
D 3685 3988 650, 670
E 2897 2556 610, 630
HR 3500 3648 =<590

In the end, these plots largely end up looking the same, without sufficient differentiation to be able to reasonably tell if either is "better" than the other. The credit bins do find a higher rate of failure for the absolute lowest credit scores than the lowest Prosper rating bin does, which I tend to think is accurate. However, the "HR" designation in Prosper ratings is problematic as mentioned previously, because it contains a very wide range of credit scores (the corresponding bin for credit bins does not) for unknown reasons.

In the end, this entire detour ended up being largely irrelevant. It is included (but labelled as such) in this report solely for completeness, as we are encouraged to include even our "dead end" explorations.

Resuming Bivariate Exploration¶

Credit score and Prosper rating were assumed to be the primary indicators of whether or not a borrower would successfully complete their loan, being composite metrics generated from a number of other statistics about that borrower. I next attempted to look into how certain metrics would compare directly with loan completion rate, starting with traditional metrics.

Borrower APR is the strongest indicator of loan completion, of these three metrics. The effects around the middle of the data are not particularly different, but we do see this relationship more clearly at the extremes of each violin. Notably, however, there are not insignificant amounts of borrowers successfully completing their loans at high APR, or failing to completing their loans at a low APR.

Looking at open lines of credit and ratios of debt to income, the violin plots for success and failure are quite similar. Open lines of credit has a slightly wider range amongst failed loans, with fewer lines of credit being somewhat surprisingly associated with failed loans, but this difference appears to be quite small. Debt-to-income ratio also has a wider range amongst failed loans, but the difference again appears fairly small.

Next, I looked at employment information and how it compared with loan status. Employment duration was zoomed to only look at <5 years of employment status, given the extremely long tail for this data. There didn't appear to be any meaningful difference between loan status and employment duration.

Similar to what I did with the previous heat maps looking at loan status, I used success/fail percentage rather than raw count. Given an overall rate of 30% of loans being failed, the different employment statuses didn't seem to deviate from this very strongly, aside from self-employment and "Unknown" having noticeably higher failure rates. As mentioned in the initial exploration of employment status, there are some problems here which make it difficult to draw meaningful conclusions. Are self employed borrowers more likely to default, or is this indicative of something else? The lack of specificity with "Employed" and "Unknown" categories make it impossible to meaningfully assess these categories relative to the rest.

Having looked at these more traditional metrics, I moved on to checking non-traditional metrics and their relationship with successful loan completion.

As previous loans with Prosper increases, the probability of a loan failing to be paid back continues to drop from the overall rate of 0.3, dropping down to failure rates of around 0.1. This trend only changes at the far extreme of 7 prior Prosper loans, but this is most likely a result of small sample size at this level, as only 5 loans exist in the dataset with 7 prior Prosper loans, with 1 of them being failed.

While "recommendations" generally seems like a fairly straightforward statistic, there's some things here that make it a bit strange. There are 3795 recommendations in the dataset, with a peak of 39 recommendations for one borrower. However, no borrower in the dataset had more than 7 prior Prosper loans, with most who had previous loans only having a couple. I find it difficult to imagine that recommendations can be freely given by other members of the community without having actually completed loans, as the metric would otherwise risk getting manipulated to misrepresent people at safer bets for credit than they otherwise would be.

We can see here that recommendations quickly drop off after 1-2 recommendations. Looking at loan completion percentage, there really doesn't appear to be any impact on loan completion for having earned recommendations on Prosper. There is a bit of higher-than-average loan completion at higher recommendation levels (5+), but we also see lower-than-average rates as well. There are only 39 datapoints at 5+ recommendations, so this data is volatile due to the small sample size. Overall, I don't think there's anything meaningful to take away from recommendations as a metric for loan completion.

Finally, I looked at the relationship between the amount invested by friends into a loan and the successful completion of that loan.

Because the amount invested is so disparate (anywhere from friends chipping in a few bucks to a friend investing \$25,000), I first plotted completion against the log of investment amount. I would've hoped to see higher rates of successful loan completion as loan amount increased, but there's no indication that this is the case.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Finishing up this exploration, I want to look at how multiple variables in this dataset interact together. This is primarily geared towards looking at how successful loan completion is related to a number of factors, both traditional and non-traditional. Given how so much of the data in this dataset is categorical, or in small enough variety of integers to graph similarly to categorical data, I'm going to largely be relying on heatmaps here. While there are some areas where I could use some alternatives, using different plots makes it difficult to compare data across plots, which is also going to be necessary due to the number of categorical (or faux-categorical) values.

Amongst the Prosper rating data (the top two plots), we can see a consistent trend towards higher success rates (and lower failure rates) as Prosper rating or income improve. This is especially evident if we ignore the "Unknown" income data (in more recent loans, Prosper makes sure to get this information) and the "HR" Prosper rating category, which we've previously discussed as being inconsistent and problematic. In both directions on these plots, we seem similar magnitude increases in success rate of around 20% increase of successful loan completion, whether going from an 'E' -> 'AA' Prosper rating, or a \$0 -> \\$100,000 income.

Looking at the credit score data (and again, ignoring the "Unknown" income column), we see an overall trend of increasing successful loan completion as we move from the bottom left (low credit, low income) to the top right (high credit, high income). This relationship between these three variables doesn't seem as consistent as it was in the above Prosper rating plots, however. At low credit scores, changes in income don't seem to increase the rate of successfully paying off a loan (in fact, there's some evidence that completion rate decreases in this area), and within an income bracket, increasing credit score doesn't really impact success rate until after passing 600 - 650 or so, with inconsistent improvements occurring across income brackets.

This is present in every Prosper rating bin, and the effect is more pronounced alongside credit score when it reaches the mid 600's, where we see a rise in success rate with credit score alone, as the two effects seem to compound.

Explanatory Data Analysis (Conclusions)¶

This project was generally unstructured, allowing students to explore their chosen dataset and present their own observations from this exploration to "tell a story" regarding the data. Having dug through numerous relationships between variables in the dataset in my exploratory data analysis, several relationships or interesting facts about the data jumped out to me that I believe merit some sort of consideration or action by Prosper. I want to concentrate on providing insight into three particular elements of the dataset, along with suggested action plans for Prosper based on the data presented here.

  • How do prior Prosper loans and friends invested in a loan relate to successful loan completion?
    These are metrics that are unique to the Prosper peer-to-peer loan platform, and better understanding and use of these metrics can provide insight into borrowers and their likelihood of successfully paying off a loan beyond the traditional metrics seen in credits/loan.

  • What value is provided by Prosper's borrower "recommendation" counts?
    This is another metric unique to the Prosper peer-to-peer loan platform, and it is the only visible "reputation" function available to judge a prospective borrower's creditworthiness, similar to such metrics on other sites like a review grade or eBay's feedback scores.

  • What trends can we see amongst the largest investors in the platform?
    Something that came up very organically in the process of this exploration was finding that there are a number of loans being fulfilled in whole by a single investor who is a "friend" of the borrower. This isn't necessarily an indication of anything bad (though it may need to be monitored to make sure this remains the case), as the opportunity to use peer-to-peer lending as an investment is a feature of some peer-to-peer lending programs. These biggest investors are outliers in the overall dataset, and their investing patterns and results can be informative regarding how the platform is (or can be) used and may be sources of insight that can be applied to the Prosper loan population at large.

How do prior Prosper loans and friends invested in a loan relate to successful loan completion?¶

CONCLUSION: The graph of success rate (left plot) is placed alongside the raw number of loans in each "bin" or "cell" (right plot) of this heatmap to provide some necessary context regarding how much weight can be placed in the accuracy of that success rate. These conclusions are concentrated on what can be concluded from the bottom left corner, as a result.

At the 0, 0 bin (0 friends invested in the loan, 0 prior Prosper loans), we see a 67% successful loan completion rate, just under the success rate we see for the overall dataset. What is extremely promising about this data is that if a borrower gets 1 friend to invest in their loan (0, 1 on the heat map), that success rate goes up about 10%, about 74% likely to pay that loan off. Similarly, if a borrower has 1 prior completed loan through Prosper (1, 0 on the heatmap), their success rate for paying off a loan also increases about 10%, to 75% chance of success.

If a borrower can get both 1 friend invested in their loan AND has 1 prior completed loan, their successful loan rate goes up another 10%. At this point, the prospective borrower has an 83% likelihood of successful repayment of the loan. While the size of this subset (1, 1) of the data is relatively small (n = 241), this is a significant improvement in success rate, and higher success rates mean safer investments for Prosper and its investing users. The data going further out (3+ along either axis) gets extremely volatile due to small sample sizes, but we do see promising trends along each axis with successful loan completion pushing towards 90%, along with the more substantive observations noted already. At a minimum, these trends merit further study, and I believe they would also merit action to better leverage their impact.

ACTION: Getting borrowers to have prior loans, or to have friends investing in their loans, seems to have a legitimate positive impact on successful loan repayment, and Prosper needs to work to incentivize both behaviors amongst borrowers.

Regarding getting friends to invest, it may behoove Prosper to prompt borrowers generating a loan listing to get their friends to sign up for the platform and invest in their loan. While this could be done with a simple prompt, I suspect that not many users do this because asking friends for a loan is awkward and can be socially harmful. A way to push past this reluctance is to offer the borrower a lower APR if a friend invests a certain amount of money, and to calculate how much this would save the borrower over the long run. This creates a financial incentive for the borrower, who we already know is in need of money. This would require adjustment of the APR between loan listing and loan fulfillment, but this shouldn't be a significant problem.

Regarding how to get more borrowers to have prior loans, this requires trying to get people into the Prosper ecosystem earlier on (perhaps with smaller loans, maybe with a certain maximum), getting them into the system and demonstrating an ability (or inability) to pay off loans successfully. I suspect that this is a marketing issue, where many people (especially those who may have lower financial literacy, which may coincide with worse credit as well) may not realize that peer-to-peer lending is an option and are simply dealing with the more exploitative elements of society and accepting it as "just the way it is". One area in particular which might be worth pursuing is marketing an alternative to the universally reviled payday loan treadmill, giving borrowers an option that allows them to stabilize their finances (and help their credit) while working to pay the loan back over a longer term than payday lenders provide.

CONCLUSION: Throughout my univariate and bivariate exploration, I noticed that 'recommendations' is a problematic statistic. I would contend that it should be removed (or at least, reset and significantly reworked) by Prosper as it is highly misleading in its current form.

In the left hand plot, we can see that as the number of recommendations increase, we do not see a trend of increasing successful loan completion. At 5+ recommendations, we're dealing with sample sizes of less than 15 (n = 1 or 2 for values beyond 9 recommendations) so the data at these points is very volatile. However, even at lower levels of recommendations, where we have a larger pool to study, we see success rates that differ only very, very slightly from the overall dataset.

Intuitively, the main way that people earn feedback or reputation on a transaction-based site is by completing transactions and being "upvoted" or "recommended" somehow. In the case of a loan, the only way to complete a transaction in a positive fashion is to successfully pay off the loan. However, the middle plot demonstrates that for almost all numbers of recommendations present in the database, the average number of loans completed by that borrower is less than 1. On what basis is a borrower able to be "recommended", when they've never borrowed money before?

In several cases (borrowers with 8, 14, 21, 24, and 39 recommendations), the borrowers had absolutely no completed loans, and yet they had very large numbers of recommendations, relative to the whole. The most egregious example is the borrower with 39 loans, whose data is provided here as an example. In this case, this borrower had 0 prior Prosper loans, and 33 friends contributed a total of \$23,699 to the borrower's \\$25,000 loan. To the borrower's credit, he or she did successfully pay off the loan, but is this person the most trustworthy person on Prosper by a country mile? Presumably, the 33 friends were among the 39 users providing recommendations to this borrower, and while there may be some value to allowing "friends" to say "Hey, my friend here is trustworthy and you should loan them your money", their investment alone already indicates this. The fact that 33 friends invested in this borrower's loan is plenty meaningful. In essence, they've already put their money where their mouth is, so allowing this borrower's friends to generate a pile of recommendations is largely irrelevant.

Finally, the last plot shows the total number of prior loans that exist in the dataset, as well as the total number of recommendations in the dataset. If each borrower who successfully completed a loan (a successful transaction) received +1 recommendation (or reputation), the two would be equal. Instead, we see that recommendations are far behind the number of prior loans, and while not all borrowers with prior loans have successfully paid off all of those prior loans, we know that 70% of borrowers pay off their loans successfully, with borrowers having prior loans doing so at a higher rate. When we take this discrepancy in conjunction with the fact that the vast majority of "recommended" borrowers have 0 previous loans at all, we can clearly conclude that recommendations are both A) not being given frequently enough to successful borrowers, and B) when they are given, they're not even being given to the right users.

ACTION: Especially on a website allowing for financial transactions between users, any measure of reputation must be stringently protected and made sure to be as "true" as possible. The apparent ability for recommendations to be collected en masse by borrowers who've not even completed a single loan allows those borrowers to potentially mislead other users who may invest in their loan. Allowing for such behavior can render the "reputation" metric irrelevant to those informed of its inaccuracy, and misleading to those who are ignorant to this problem, such as new users of the platform. At a minimum, this harms the user experience, and at worst, it could potentially lead to legal liability for Prosper. The metric has only negative value, and as a result, it must be removed from the service, at least until it can be sufficiently modified to provide a positive value to users.

CONCLUSION: In the univariate exploration of the amount invested into a borrower's loan by their friends, the majority of the investments was about what would be expected - mostly in the range of a couple hundred, with a few listings managing to get a few thousand out of friends and family as a sort of crowdfunding. However, 95 results were found with a single friend providing the full investment of the loan, which was unexpected.

The left hand plot shows the amounts being loaned by these single investors, ranging from \$1,000 at the minimum to \\$25,000 at the maximum. Prosper's peer-to-peer lending model allows for investors to use the service as an investment like any other, so this sort of behavior is not against any rules, though it is unusual because it represents an aggressive strategy where many investors may want to mitigate their risk by diversifying their investments across borrowers. This can also indicate that people are using the platform as a way to formalize loan agreements between friends, which is also an intended use of the service. With the size of some of the investments happening here, it would be prudent for Prosper to keep a close eye on their most extreme transactions to ensure that Prosper is not being used as a vehicle for some sort of illicit activity, such as money laundering. There is potentially more to be learned here though, as it seems that these investors are being more successful in their investments than the overall population on Prosper.

The middle plot shows the rate of successful loan completion for the overall Prosper dataset (about 69%), relative to the same rate for the completed loans made by a fully invested single friend (79%). This is an improvement of just under 15%, and while the sample size is small (n = 95 for these loans), it is a promising result and certainly worthy of further investigation.

On any failed loan, there is a consideration of magnitude of failure for that loan for investors. If a loan of \$10,000 is made, it's a better result for the investor for the borrower to have paid off 75\% of that loan, rather than 25\%, as the investor's loss is reduced in this circumstance. The right plot shows the average percentage of loan principal lost for both the group of fully invested single friends and the overall Prosper dataset. In addition to their larger overall success rate on loans, this group is enjoying a significantly improved rate of principal loss amount compared to the overall population of Prosper investors. Where a failed loan on Prosper results in an average loss of 71\% of the principal loaned, these investors see an average loss on their failed loans of just 49\% of the principal loaned. Across these two graphs, it's clear that this particular group of investors is taking fewer losses overall, and when they are taking a loss, the magnitude of that loss is significantly reduced.

ACTION: As mentioned, Prosper should be keeping a close eye on these most extreme users to ensure that nothing untoward is happening which may generate liability for Prosper or create a negative experience for users. While this is unlikely, it is prudent to govern oneself responsibly rather than to be taken advantage of or to have governance imposed upon a company (or the peer-to-peer lending industry as a whole) after an issue is brought to light.

In keeping a close eye on these largest investors, it would also behoove Prosper to more closely examine how these investors are making their investment decisions, as such insights could help better quantify borrowers' risk for loan failure in the future. The publically provided dataset is almost exclusively concentrated on data about borrowers, with little to analyze from investors. For example, there is no way to tell whether or not one person made all 95 of these investments, or if 95 people made all 95 investments. This data, as well as other data regarding what information an investor has access to about a borrower, time spent researching loan listings, and any other gathered data about these investors would be extremely useful to try to understand the insight that these investors seem to have.

Limitations of Analysis¶

The analysis presented in this report is subject to two primary limitations, in addition to the ordinary concerns about the accuracy of collected data on which the report is based, etc.

The first significant limitation of this report is that this binary scoring of loans as successful or not could be an oversimplification of the data. As mentioned, there are actually two components to a failed loan: was the loan failed, and if so, how bad was it? This analysis concentrated almost exclusively on the first portion of that equation, with little exploration of how the variables in this report impacted the second question. A subsequent report would be necessary to address this second question regarding the financial impact of failed loans.

Another significant limitation of this data is that it is only handling completed loans over the time period of Apr 2006 - Feb 2014. The nature of finished loans is that they are older than current loans, meaning that this dataset is overall older than current data would be. Additionally, the data collected by Prosper changed quite a bit over this time, as did other user data not included here, I'm sure. There may be circumstances where a change has occurred at some point during this dataset (or since) which was not accounted for in this analysis, which treated the data as being largely homogenized. An example of such a change that I found when Googling to get information about Prosper at one point is that they apparently now require a credit score of 640 to get loans. Any such changes should be considered prior to implementing action plans recommended by this report.
